title.narrative: ADOLESCENT HEALTH

description.narrative: The Government demonstrates strengthened capacity to ensure adolescent have improved access to gender-responsive and culturally- competent physical, mental, sexual and reproductive health services and information, which contributes to Cross-Sectoral - Monitoring, Data And Situation Analyses, Cross-Sectoral - Social And Behaviour Change, Evaluation, Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid), Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Research. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, more children, adolescents and women, particularly the most vulnerable, benefit from improved and equitable neonatal, child, maternal and adolescent health and nutrition services, and adopt healthy life practices.

description.narrative: UNICEF strengthened government’s effort to promote and protect critical determinant of health and well-being of adolescent through the development and pilot-testing of Adolescent Sexual and Reproductive Health (ASRH) Playbooks, a ready-to-use tools for the;LGUs;and providing technical advice to ensure guidelines are practical and implementable at the local level. Strengthening further the community support for ASRH, 2.2 million young people and 113 duty bearers were engaged on virtual community-led health projects on adolescent health and HIV. At the subnational level, UNICEF used capacity building expertise to support 4 LGUs to mobilize and empower networks of young people to access health-related projects. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:23/12/2021
